The goal of this exercise is it to gain a shell exploiting the binary compiled from the referenced code base. Source: https://github.com/edgecase1/potato2

Use a Linux operating system to compile the binary. It is allowed to compile it with 

executable stack (-z execstack) 
without stack canaries (-fno-stack-protector)  
ASLR disabled (echo 0 | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/randomize_va_space) -no-pie
Your tasks:

identify a vulnerability and explain it in detail. What insecure function/programming practice is used and are there restrictions? How can the vulnerability exploited? [2 points]
create a payload to change the instruction pointer. Explain how you came up with the correct payload size. Set it to a predefined value (you can choose an internal function address). [2 points]
start a shell using shellcode (on the stack) using a stack-based buffer overflow attack [3]
start a shell using a stack-based-buffer overflow using a ret2libc attack [4]
create a custom shellcode or run a ROP attack. You may link the program statically [3]
Resources:

Python template (uses pwntools)
RIP overwrite 
Introduction to x64 Linux Binary Exploitation (Part 1)
Ret2libc
Introduction to x64 Linux Binary Exploitation (Part 2)—return into libc
ROP
Introduction to x64 Linux Binary Exploitation (Part 3)- RoP Chains
Shellcode
see file attached (exec /bin/sh working on X86-64)
